A few decades before the Surrealists began painting their dreamlike works, Henri Rousseau was meticulously crafting his own dreams in both literal and figurative ways. The Dream, a painting from 1910 by the renowned Post-Impressionist, depicts not just a woman in awe of the wonders she experiences in a dream, but also Rousseau’s own dreams and aspirations as an artist. Ever since he started his journey, he longed for recognition, acceptance, and praise from fellow artists and art lovers, only to confront a challenging internal conflict: to either imitate existing styles to gain acceptance or to forge his own unique path. The Dream encapsulates Rousseau’s lifelong struggle with this dilemma.

To truly understand The Dream, we must first delve into Rousseau’s life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France, his father was a prosperous tinsmith and hardware dealer. He grew up without formal art training and worked as a gabelou for France until the age of forty, erroneously known as a douanier, or customs inspector. After the loss of his first wife and eight children, Rousseau turned to painting for solace and new beginnings. Unlike many of his contemporaries, who romanticized the peasant in their paintings, Rousseau was a folk artist, reflecting the aspirations and dreams of the common class.

Rousseau's desire for acceptance by the art world is understandable given his background: he was uneducated in formal painting and began his career later in life, working alongside more established and recognized artists. It was not until around the same time that Matisse was building his reputation that Rousseau started to gain recognition for his art. As Jan Gordon notes in Modern French Painters, “Matisse was a painter who feared painting in a conventional way, while Rousseau strove to paint in a conventional manner to be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Another thing that's captured my attention is the deep connection between ethics and aesthetics that many great thinkers have explored. It's not just about education or experience, but something more profound. As John Keats put it in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Ethics and aesthetics seem to talk to each other without us even realizing it. We often study art and morals to understand why something is beautiful or right, rather than to prescribe specific rules for beauty or morality. Even when we try to describe what makes a masterpiece like the Mona Lisa great, we often find ourselves saying, "There's just something about it" before diving into a more complex explanation. This is because art and morals can't be fully captured by description alone. Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Both art and morals have this transcendent quality, this ineffable "something" that makes them so powerful. This "something" is what connects ethics and aesthetics. I believe this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics is the reason they feel so deeply impactful, especially when it comes to literature. As McKean argues, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts... is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Germany in its present form is a powerful, united country, with a rich cultural tapestry that weaves through its landscape, from the scenic Alps in München to the Baltic Sea coastal city of Kiel. This unique blend of culture is evident whether you are in Köln by the Rhine, the heart of Germany, or the historical city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given the diverse origins of its inhabitants, it's not surprising that Germany, as we know it today, is a fusion of various tribes and influences.

The origins of the name "Germania" are shrouded in historical debate. Some scholars claim it comes from the Germanic tribe known as Tungrians, who were once called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and clashed with the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar, in his accounts of the Gallic Wars, first used the term "Germanus" to distinguish between the conquered Gauls and the Germanic tribes who frequently crossed the Rhine (Caesar, 50-40 BC). Others suggest the name is derived from the German spear, known as a "ger" (O.E.D., 2010), or from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," implying the Germans were loud or warlike (Names of Germany).

The early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," described the Germans as "aboriginal" and not mixed with other races through immigration. He questioned why anyone would leave the warm climates of Asia or Africa for the harsher lands of Germany, with its wild terrain, harsh weather, and stern demeanor (Tacitus, 98). The Romans, while they often raided German lands for resources, generally preferred to return to their own empire rather than settle in Germania (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

As the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the outskirts of the Roman Empire. They traded their land-grown goods and served in the Roman army, integrating their skills and culture into the Roman fold (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

I looked down at the view in front of me, my mind as blank as the scene itself. Silently, unemotionally, with a practiced eye that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding, I analyzed the picture. Thoughts flowed in and out like a gentle stream. It was as if I had no thoughts of my own, just an active and fluid experience of what I was seeing. Once, an artist I worked with suggested I get a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had always wanted to learn to draw, and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to the brain's processes for interpreting lines. One technique it teaches is to place a square frame around any picture to simplify it. At that moment, standing there, I couldn't mentally project that frame. I was too overwhelmed, too awed. I felt like I was at the beginning of my own artistic journey, starting my own story. Fingertips lightly touched my chosen art tool, muscles tensed and relaxed as I began to recreate the scene in my mind. Water swirled smoothly, crystals clear and clean. A flurry of matter broke away, carried away to nothingness. My hand smacked the handle again, the brown package still stubbornly in place. A few more flushes, a few more moments of quiet thought, and then I gripped the toilet paper like a gloved hand. I stood up, then bent at the waist, and slowly dipped my hand into the bowl, like a mother retrieving a Thanksgiving turkey from the oven...

Another grim trend has emerged among our youth, one that's been claiming lives behind the wheel. Several elements converge to create this deadly pattern for our youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health highlight that the teen brain is simply not equipped to handle the perils of driving, and this lack of experience leads to more fatal accidents, as well as a higher rate of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. But the hazards don't stop there—teens are even more vulnerable when driving with their friends, a fact that anyone with an inkling of common sense understands. Studies have shown that the presence of passengers, especially teens, significantly increases the risk of accidents. California and other states have implemented measures like temporary provisional licenses, limiting driving hours and passengers, but these are merely Band-Aids. The core issue is that, collectively, our youngest drivers aren't ready to handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman even suggests that 18 is too young for a standard driver's license, citing research that shows teens under 19-20 often seek out thrills and risks. Therefore, delaying driving until this tendency subsides could help reduce accidents and save lives. By 2010, the first wave of Baby Boomer's children will be eligible to drive, potentially adding millions of new teen drivers to the roads. A sensible solution is to continue driver's education classes in schools, but no one under 18 should be allowed to drive a vehicle. Provisional permits could still be issued, with a set number of practical driving hours required, mirroring existing state requirements. Uniform, national legislation could help protect teens across the country. This approach is not a new idea.

After sifting through the Library of Congress’s treasure trove of early Edison films, I made it my mission to watch all the trick films from 1895 to 1901, numbering fifteen in total. These films are known for their clever use of editing to create illusions. My study primarily focused on describing the poetic elements of the bulk of these trick films and exploring the unique qualities of a few of the latter films. Most trick films from this era adhere to a set-bound style, confined within a frontal proscenium, with no camera movement, and utilizing long and medium shots. They stick to the one shot equals one film method. However, some films at the dawn of the twentieth century were bold enough to break these norms by incorporating multiple shots.

One common thread among these trick films is their use of an interior set confined within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationery, not moving to follow figures or objects. This style finds its roots in the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. The constraint of the stage means that figures in trick films usually move side-to-side, never walking towards or away from the camera. A clear example is the action in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). Actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis, but the camera never follows them out of the frame.

The frontal proscenium style also dictates that shots are typically long and occasionally medium shots. Close-ups are absent from all the trick films in the Edison catalog. This is a nod to the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where audiences saw the entire performance at once, framed by the stage borders. As in most early films, actors don’t move towards the camera, so close-ups are non-existent.

Most early trick films follow the rule that one conceptual shot equates to one film. This caps the length at about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second. It also limits the dramatic or narrative scope of the films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. However, in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes doesn’t correspond to a physical shot. A single “shot” may actually be composed of several joined together to create illusions of apparition or disappearing. Examine The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A closer look reveals that the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” begins, even though the film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

So John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate for Republicanism. Though primarily an agriculturalist, his career in politics greatly influenced his dedication and vocal support for personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system shaped his views on sovereignty, Constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

Taylor saw the United States as a unique opportunity to create an ideal system, unhampered by traditional constraints, allowing for self-government. He firmly believed in the natural rights of man, asserting their interdependence—if one is denied, the rest fail, and their remaining value diminishes. These rights should remain beyond government reach. He argued that the "state of nature" allowed the powerful and malevolent to thrive, but civilization must prevent this.

To establish an ideal society, Taylor believed a government should account for human goodness and evil. He was rigid in his dualistic morality, claiming, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). Good principles, like protecting private property and agriculture, and discouraging capitalism, were fundamental. A government founded on these principles would function fairly despite its administration's self-interest.

Taylor, like other Republicans of his time, advocated for a strict construction of the Constitution. He wanted a minimal Federal Government, with no rights or powers beyond those explicitly stated. He recognized potential corruption in a literal interpretation without considering the writers' intent. He considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter, as it described the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Alright, so let's revisit Figure 17. A major dip in commuter log submissions happened in the third month of our project. That was a bit of a bummer, and the reason behind it? Well, it's a bit unclear. The New England winter might've been the culprit, with fewer folks commuting by bike or on foot. Plus, December is the end of the semester, leaving many with schoolwork and grades on their minds, possibly causing the log to slip their radar. On top of that, the holiday season brings a month-long break for students and faculty, with many not needing to come to campus at all. Classes resume in late January, which could explain the low February log submissions. But what about the February dip? It could just be a natural ebb and flow of excitement with any new project. To combat this, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which did bring back some of our log submissions. So, we faced the challenge of keeping the momentum going despite holiday breaks and a decline in natural excitement. Another big issue for this or any similar project is the deep cultural love for the freedom and flexibility of driving. To counter this, we offered various prizes like gift cards to local places. It'd be awesome to see if bigger prizes like a bicycle, hybrid, or electric car would've boosted participation. The value of the prizes didn't change throughout the project, but announcing bigger prizes later might've helped. The gift cards were great at the start, but adding some bicycles and cars as bigger prizes could've been a game-changer.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a type of investment that is designed to mimic the performance of an index, a commodity, or a group of assets, similar to an index fund. However, unlike index funds, ETFs trade like stocks on an exchange. This setup offers several advantages: the diversification of an index fund, the flexibility of selling short, buying on margin, and the ability to purchase as few as one share at a time. While these benefits are enticing, it's important to note that ETFs come with a downside—the need to pay a commission on trades, much like stock orders. Additionally, ETFs offer a wide range of funds to choose from. However, as a savvy investor, it's crucial to assess whether the stated advantages, such as diversification, genuinely exist and to what extent they do so.

For this analysis, let's examine the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of its total assets. The top holdings and their respective percentages are as follows:

To gauge how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF, we can calculate the contribution of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio were composed entirely of these 10 stocks in the same proportions that the ETF has established. The Beta and Return calculations for each stock are shown in the chart below.

From this chart, it's clear that a portfolio consisting only of the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, a 16% increase. Moreover, the Beta of this portfolio is 0.12 points lower than the ETF's overall Beta. These initial results suggest that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower risk, but it's essential to determine if these portfolios are statistically different from one another.

To assess this, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their combined standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Poe's poem "Dream-Land" is often regarded as one of his superior works. Within it, he employs the term "Thulé," which Mabbott attributes to Virgil. Virgil referred to an island north of Britain, marking the edge of the known world. While Virgil indeed used the term, a more recent and significant influence should be recognized. Poe was deeply interested in German literature, particularly the works of Goethe.

This knowledge is significant because it reveals Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," notes the similarities between the two poets' works, suggesting that Poe was inspired by Goethe. Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned writer of poetic drama, including his magnum opus "Faust," published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of his death. Within "Faust," Part II contains a short poem titled "The King of Thule," which tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. Overwhelmed by sorrow, he drinks heavily and cries, then decides to end his life by throwing the goblet into the sea. His actions and the description of the king in "Dream-Land" bear a striking resemblance, hinting at a dark reflection of Poe's own experiences.

Poe references "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but in "Dream-Land," he uses the term as a framing device. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a dark, lonely landscape where he is haunted by deceased friends, which mirrors the feelings of the king in "The King of Thule." Both poems depict a world without color and life, suggesting that the speaker has stepped into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was an influential author, and Poe would have been exposed to his work through various reproductions and his admiration for Tennyson, whom Poe greatly respected. When asked if he admired Tennyson, Poe's response underscored his familiarity with German literature and the works of Goethe.

Alright, another thing I'd like to talk about is this legal conundrum. Could a customer injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by showing the store manager acted with malice? Well, under California law, it's not a clear-cut case. To prove punitive damages, the plaintiff needs to show that the defendant's actions were intentional and that they were committed with a willful disregard for the probable harm that would result. In Jennifer Palmer's case, she fell on an applesauce spill that was reported twice to the manager, Paul Martin, but he failed to clean it up because he was eating dinner. Six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in the store before Palmer's accident, so it's reasonable for her to argue that Martin should have known the risk and still failed to act. However, proving that Martin's actions were despicable might be more challenging. But given the circumstances, her claim is not without merit.

Four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC where a significant topic of debate was whether Islam is inherently hostile. This discussion remains pertinent today. Since 9/11, I've witnessed a shift in media portrayal, from hostility towards both Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance toward Islam in America. In 2001, it would've been unthinkable to imagine a presidential candidate with the name Barack Obama, who has a Muslim background in his family.

The life story of Muhammad, as presented in the biography, is intriguing but seems to contradict historical accounts. From what I know, Muhammad was depicted as a forceful figure who conquered tribes and coerced them into adopting Islam. However, the biography portrays him as a martyr, misunderstood and humble, who attracted followers through his teachings and miracles. This portrayal seems designed to present him as a humble prophet who needed no proof but was centered around truth and miracles. This approach trivializes the life and miracles of Jesus, as if Muhammad is being used to take credit for Jesus' life and personhood.

Additionally, many stories in the biography suggest an agenda to provide evidence of voluntary conversions. However, these accounts often come from third-party sources, which I find suspicious. For instance, the author might claim to have heard from someone who heard it from someone else, weakening the credibility of the stories.

What bothers me most is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle man. Historical records suggest otherwise, and I can't help but wonder if current Muslims are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

So, the lessons Jesus taught and his beliefs during his life have been left behind in the evolution of Christian thought, which has since moved on from its roots after his life. If we look at the broader picture, we see that Christianity has strayed further and further from its origin over time. Today's world shows an increasing awareness and unprecedented progressiveness. While traditional people and thinkers still exist and might resist any new ideas, they may not have the influence to shape the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow significantly in the coming years. There will be a growing desire to distinguish the doctrines that have been added to Christianity over time from the original intent of the religion's founder. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome is inevitable: a reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a movement that removes layers of doctrine, one by one, as if the clock is turning back, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God remains, before any other thinkers made such claims. When this trend spreads through the United States and Europe, influencing masses to worship as if they were living at the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme proliferation of diversity in Christendom will reverse into more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of every kind, we will see increasing similarities instead of differences. Human history is filled with great reversions. An example is how Christians once were persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has gone from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play itself out in the arena of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source, and undoing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible will be a method of reading Jesus' words as metaphorical, and not as literal statements. So, what happened after Jesus' lifetime?

Looking far back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were all at the core of the religion even as the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

Oh, so The Jungle, it's all about how humans, deep down, are greedy and self-centred, huh? They're all about making their own lives as cushy as possible, never mind who gets stepped on along the way. Sinclair makes it crystal clear with his descriptions of the factory owners and managers. They're just after big, fat profits, not caring a whit about anyone or anything in their path, including the pollution they spew out. "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," he writes. They couldn't care less about the smoke, the animal waste, or even the people they're exploiting.

And the workers? Well, they're just tools for these greedy folks to make money with. They'll do anything to squeeze out an extra buck, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar". Workers are forced to work in appalling conditions, with no job security and no safety net. Back then, there were barely any laws protecting workers' rights, so managers could run amok, pushing workers to the breaking point. And if you can't handle it, well, tough luck. There were no unions to help, just more people looking to make a buck off the workers' misery. It was a system of slavery, plain and simple, with workers "dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors have their own methods to evoke certain feelings or ideas in their readers, with some techniques proving more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs a variety of these methods in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, he combines an adjective and a noun in an unusual way to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. Other times, he imbues a symbol with meaning and then uses it to convey that same meaning. Fitzgerald frequently uses this latter technique with colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In his novel, he attributes specific meanings to white/gray and red/pink before later employing those meanings to evoke feelings around important objects.

Fitzgerald associates white/gray with uniformity, with white being slightly more elegant and refined, and gray representing something older and worn. He establishes this connection at the beginning of the novel by repeatedly using both colors. Daisy and Jordan are continually “in white” (8), and everyone else is dressed in white as well: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). The only exceptions are when Nick is observing Gatsby’s party: "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). He also uses these colors to describe ordinary objects and people: the “names” at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray” (61) on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—uniformity (28). He uses white/gray to describe ordinary or common people and places, such as Daisy and Jordan having a “white girlhood” (19), the “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, the “Italian child” is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).

After building up these meanings, Fitzgerald employs them to signify unimportance or uniformity for certain subjects. This use of colors to convey meaning starts with Daisy. After a prolonged period without significant use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster,” causing readers to perceive her as less of a character and more like a uniform object that Gatsby desires and longs for (74). He continues this technique around Daisy to emphasize her uniformity, for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is pretty much a powerhouse when it comes to agriculture, with its mild and sunny climate. The area's main crops include tomatoes, lemons, peaches, berries, honey, and a variety of leafy greens, squash, broccoli, and peppers. There's a pretty solid demand in the area for organic, community-supported agriculture, with many local groups having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also quite popular. Many organic farms here offer tours of their operations and access for activities like hiking and birdwatching, which can help the landowner make some extra cash or provide educational experiences. This kind of setup would let the landowner benefit from government programs while also improving habitat, providing recreational activities, and creating opportunities for farm tours and other programs.

So, culture, it's a big deal in any negotiation. It's not something you can define with one word or one stereotype. It's like saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating," right? That's way too broad and simple. Instead, it's better to understand how a culture affects the conversation at hand and how it plays into the negotiation. When you're dealing with a foreign culture, you'll compare it to your own, and that's normal. But it's important not to judge or change a culture, but to work within it, especially if you're at a disadvantage.

Understanding a culture can mean looking into its past or seeing its prejudices. You don't have to agree with them or try to change them, just accept them for what they are. And when you're in a foreign environment, respect can go a long way in breaking down cultural barriers and moving the negotiation forward.

Culture isn't just about national boundaries. Companies also have their own cultures. Some might value long work hours, others a relaxed schedule. You can see a company's culture in how employees dress, how they communicate, and how they hire. Even within the same country, there's a lot of diversity. For example, American companies can have very different cultures. Some might encourage employee philanthropy, others might restrict it. The point is, a lot of thought goes into the culture of a society or a company.

Values are key too, because they tell you why a culture is the way it is. If a culture values saving face or communal harmony, you won't publicly shame anyone at the negotiation table. And if a culture values a hard-driven bargain, you won't settle too quickly. Understanding these generalities before you start negotiating can really help. But it's also important to learn about your opponent on a personal level to make the negotiation effective.

So, as it stands, let's assume that both St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas are onto something with their beliefs in the existence of the God of the Bible. After all, they're both arguing for the same thing, so we'll start with that premise. However, I'm not convinced that either of them really gives a solid foundation for believing in God. Let's break it down.

First, let's take a look at St. Anselm's argument. He's all about finding God within ourselves, using our own understanding to prove his existence. He says that because God is within our comprehension, we can't really grasp his nonexistence. It's a bit convoluted, but the gist is that we don't need external evidence to know God is real; we just need to look inside ourselves. This is essentially faith, as it's accepting something without irrefutable proof.

Now, contrast that with Thomas Aquinas. He's all about reason and empirical evidence. He believes we can prove God's existence using logic, without any faith. This is super handy for conversions, as we can convince people with reasoning alone. He's got five arguments for God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. He shows that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for his existence.

So, while they both have valid points, I think neither really gives a complete picture for believing in God.

In the fifth or sixth century BCE, a future Buddha was born. Over his lifetime, he gave up the world, attained enlightenment, and his teachings became Buddhism, specifically Theravada Buddhism, which has existed for around twenty-five hundred years. The religion, from its customs to its core beliefs, has evolved since Buddha's time. For instance, in Sri Lanka, a Theravada nation, an annual water-cutting ceremony is celebrated, a practice Buddha never taught. Differences extend from superficial traditions to the religion's essence. Both monastic and lay communities have had to adjust their doctrines over time due to external and internal influences, both friendly and hostile.

This discussion will frequently use terms like internal and external forces. Internal forces come from Buddhists, regardless of their status, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces harm or aim to harm the Buddhist community, born of a negative perception of Buddhism. Benign forces, while not intentionally helping or harming, may do so as a result.

Let's start by understanding the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. The Dhamma, composed of the Tripitaka—three baskets of Buddhist texts—includes the Sutta Pitaka (Suttas), Vinaya Pitaka (disciplinary rules), and Abhidhamma Pitaka (metaphysical components like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering, and Anicca—impermanence of all things). Recognizing these concepts helps end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and cease lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, upon enlightenment.

The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for life. Laypeople follow five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not consume intoxicating substances), while monks follow many more rules. The four noble truths form the fundamental doctrine: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The height of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States defeated Mexico and gained new territories like Texas and the American Southwest (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). Apart from this war, there were numerous other skirmishes between the two nations that finally subsided just before World War I.

This scenario is not unique to the U.S. and Mexico; many nations that share a border often have disputes due to shared interests. David M. Pletcher (1977) points out that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41), stressing the closeness of these nations to the U.S. and their historic rivalries, unlike other Latin American nations which have typically enjoyed good relations with the U.S.

Religious issues were a significant factor in the rivalry between the U.S. and Mexico, much like the Cold War between the U.S. and the Soviet Union. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). The enduring distrust between the U.S. and Mexico can be traced back to the historical tension between the English and Spanish, which carried over into their colonial legacies.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) document 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during their 57-year rivalry, with most of these disputes being territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a persistent problem until both nations exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to wane as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109) and ended as American ambitions shifted "from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico" (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly struck down by an illness that I had never known existed. I was a nurse at the time, having chosen my profession out of a deep-seated need for the safety and security that eluded me as a child. The mantra I heard as I grew older was, "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." So, even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist—preferably a bit of both—I chose nursing.

Yet there I was: 46‭ ‬years old, single, with no money to speak of, and unable to work. To this day, I am disabled, and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability, I have absolutely nothing left that I can call my own. I manage to get by, but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet there's one thing I know to be true—I could not have made it through these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you do not feel very strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life—big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well one prepares, some things are just too big to overcome on one's own.

I wholeheartedly agree that we in the U.S. need to stop relying so heavily on big government. Lord knows it's crumbling. Yet, I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again—learning to help each other and to ask for help—rather than each of us individually scrambling to build fallout shelters in our backyards.

The Conservatives in the US talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country, but in truth, what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism, it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit—first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and plastic sheeting for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and batteries, candle and waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

So, why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there limits or constraints that guide evolutionary change? While in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson stated that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," the same can still be said today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny, for example, as seen in Raup and Stanley's work from 1981. Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help understand the mechanisms behind the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to define quantitative parameters that could be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell. We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a tube that extends through 360 degrees of space over time. These turns or revolutions of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis called the columella. The columella runs through the central column of the shell. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, known as a suture. The largest whorl of a shell is typically the last one, called the body whorl, with the spire being all the whorls except the last one. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is the base. The animal exits its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different angles: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture pointing toward the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first view the shell from the apical view and determine where the first suture begins. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts, then count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl if necessary.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures traveling through time and space as the animal builds its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced via the coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture, as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, parameters can be varied and modified to alter the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

Well, another decade has passed, and Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates haven't moved an inch. While the country's on track to meet many of the Millennium Development Goals, like water and sanitation, the progress in child and maternal health has been dismally slow, falling short of the target. Let's delve into the reasons behind these shortcomings and the urgent need to bolster the overall health system rather than just focusing on specific programs.

Looking at the numbers, it's clear that Indonesia's progress in having skilled birth attendants is somewhat misleading. While 72% of births now have a skilled worker present, traditional midwives can't provide medical interventions, leading to a high maternal death rate from hemorrhage. Additionally, there's a decline in treating diarrheal cases in children under five. Postnatal care data is also incomplete, but it's evident that this area needs attention, with low rates across the country. Cesarian-section rates are still low, at 4%, but there's a worrying discrepancy between urban and rural areas, with a 5% rate in cities and only 2% in rural settings. This inequity in access to healthcare is clear, as is the stark difference in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, with a 27% gap.

When considering next steps for improving neonatal and maternal care, a crucial question is how to tackle the service gap effectively. Should Indonesia focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the health system as a whole? Programmatic approaches are attractive because they offer targeted, manageable goals and quicker results. However, investing heavily in one area can lead to funding shortages and human resource migration to better-resourced sectors. Plus, running multiple parallel programs can cause duplications and uncoordinated services, resulting in increased paperwork.

So, there's a need to balance these approaches and consider both.

Victorian literature is known for its meticulous attention to detail and its focus on the aristocracy. Two notable exceptions to this norm are 'Oliver Twist' and 'Wuthering Heights'. These works add an element of mystery and a hint of the unusual, which helps to deepen the characters within each story, providing insight into their motivations and emotions.

“And now, a multitude of bewildering and confusing thoughts rushed into his mind. It seemed as if he was still walking between Sikes and Crackit, arguing fiercely. The very words they spoke echoed in his ears, and he realized that he was actually talking to them. Suddenly, he recoiled at the sound of gunshots. Shouts and screams filled his ears, and lights flashed before his eyes, everything was chaos and commotion, as an unseen force carried him away quickly. Throughout these vivid visions, a constant, vague sense of pain gnawed at him, tormenting him endlessly.
(Dickens, 220)

These novels often use dream sequences or dreamlike states to incorporate this mystery. In 'Oliver Twist', these strange occurrences reveal Oliver's inner turmoil, his pains, and his awareness of the true nature of the events happening around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, it happens as if in a dream, as he struggles to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the events, as well as the dire state his health had reached, as seen through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overpowers him, numbing his senses, and he doesn't notice the “unseen hand” that bears him away. He re-experiences his despair again, removed from the initial shock of pain, now linked with constant fear. The question arises about whose will brought about his misfortune, as it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, even while his life is in danger. A sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied, suggesting that old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair and influencing his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for the sake of his own life.

“The day passed – or did it? There was no day; it was gone as soon as it began – and night came on again; a night that was endless yet fleeting, long in its dreadful silence and brief in its hurried hours.

A couple of years back, I was working in an after-school program, tutoring younger kids. I did my best to assist them in their studies, but my strongest subjects were English and reading. I was asked by one of the instructors to help a young boy named Adrian, who was struggling with reading. He was in third or fourth grade and spoke perfect English, which made his reading difficulties particularly puzzling. At first, I thought Adrian had some peculiar problems. He could pronounce some letters correctly, but others, not at all. It was strange. He was of Latino descent, and I knew his mother only spoke Spanish. When she came to pick him up, I realized his issue was not with reading but with knowing the English alphabet. I don't know if that revelation helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier problem in schools, especially in California. It's often not as clear-cut as we think, even for a child who speaks perfect English. Reading can still be a real challenge. This issue is acknowledged, but what can we do about it? In Adrian's case, the solution was simple: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. But for many children who barely speak English, the solution is far more complex. There isn't a one-size-fits-all answer. Combining dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, or any of these methods alone won't fix the problem. The key is to combine all these approaches.

Firstly, the dual language system is a fantastic idea, not only for children whose first language is Spanish but for all children. Studies have shown that children in these programs outperform their peers academically. This idea is often feared as a waste of resources, but that's not accurate. If implemented widely, all children would benefit. How, though? Should we make all teachers bilingual? No, that's unreasonable. However, having bilingual aides or tutors available would be a practical solution.

Since childhood, many of us are told about a force greater than ourselves, something we can't fully understand. Some learn about it at Sunday school, others at the Temple, or delve within themselves for answers. Often, we follow the religions passed down by our parents, but some reject them outright, denying any existence beyond our personal, egocentric worlds. Our values and belief systems may shift over time, but our spiritual journeys are uniquely ours. We search for light to guide us out of the darkness. "A cardinal," my father replied when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on our porch, listening to the rain, our cigarettes offering a brief respite from the tension. He looked out into the storm, his gaze both searching and remembering. His body was gaunt, his hair sparse. I couldn't bring myself to talk about his passing, afraid it would make the reality more tangible. I hugged him, repositioned my chair, and stared into the falling rain together.

My father passed away in December, just days after I turned twenty-two. The chemo and radiation had prolonged his suffering but not eased it. I couldn't watch my father's life end. I wanted to remember him as he lived, not die. I hid in my bed for three days, waiting for news. No one called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is essentially an "oxymoronic fusion of 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt points out in his book The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both reviled and lauded, accused of being shallow, and praised for its 'terrible sublime' effect (Burke). The original Gothic Novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined elements of both "ancient and modern" romances to birth the proto-Gothic genre and a novel way of literary expression. Walpole utilizes "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he calls "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily on throwbacks to medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and time periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary advancements. This combination of more theatrical "Gothic" and the new format of the novel (allowing readers a deeper insight into character psychology) is what keeps Gothic literature enduring and both obsolete and fresh to readers from different times.

One of the most distinctive Gothic themes is the notion of Chivalry. The medieval concept of chivalry, the training of a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is particularly significant to Gothic writers because it represents the ideal knight—brave, honorable, and competent—and the perceived lack of these qualities in contemporary society. Through the use of chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized, hinting at the evolution of Gothic to Romantic literature, and is used to attempt to improve the present. Walpole, who wrote The Castle of Otranto during a politically troubled time and was despairing over the future, may have felt that the supposed morality and innate "goodness" of the gothic era had been lost in the individuals of 'present' society. This concept is evident in several characters, such as Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits. The reader learns that Frederic is a prince, has suffered tragedy, and is now believed to be killed by infidels, embodying the figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" (66).

So, supply chain management is all about the flow of goods from a customer's order to raw materials, through production, distribution, and finally, the customer. The term was coined in 1982 by a consultant named Keith Oliver. He saw it as the planning, implementation, and control of the entire process to meet customer needs swiftly and efficiently. Now, there are six key elements to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These are the tools business managers use to deliver top-notch customer service. Let's break it down:

Production is the first step in the chain. It's the backbone, outlining when, why, where, and how things get made. Managers need to know what customers want, so they look at the market. The market is the biggest indicator of what customers demand. Once they've analyzed it, they decide what to produce and how much. Then comes the location – where and which plant will be best for volume and quality, keeping the customer in mind. After that, it's about scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is crucial, every detail matters. For instance, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target. Both had detailed processes for everything from uniforms to receiving shipments. These processes help keep things running smoothly with clear direction and expectations.

The second key element is supply. This is about making strategic decisions to determine a facility's core capabilities and decide on outsourcing partnerships. A company might have several divisions for a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers decide which division is best for each process. They might also outsource work to other companies to create velocity – providing quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low costs.

So, another shocking truth has come to light. There's a sign in Burma reading, "Hitler is alive in Burma." Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stood alone on a street corner with a cardboard sign, the message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country under the control of a tyrannical military junta that seized power in 1962. Just a decade ago, the country saw widespread public protests led by Buddhist monks. These peaceful gatherings, known as "The Saffron Revolution," turned violent, with the military cracking down on the monks and ransacking monasteries. Foreign journalists were arrested and a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was killed for being present at a protest. The official death toll is 13, but a defected colonel puts the number closer to several thousand.

This isn't new; it's a recurring theme throughout history. From early Roman emperors declaring themselves gods to the current U.S. president consulting with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, governments have always sought to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control. Notable instances include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests in China, where the official death toll ranges from 200 to 3,000, and the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the government, systematically murdered Tutsis. Nazi Germany's "Third Reich" is another extreme example, during which anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed. It's a grim reminder of the lengths governments will go to protect their power.

Well, Duke Ellington's influence on jazz is primarily due to his perseverance and exceptional talent at orchestrating his band. His subtle presence on the piano in many tracks is overshadowed by his brilliance as a composer. Ellington was a master at crafting complex pieces that highlighted the unique skills of his musicians. He established a framework where soloists could freely improvise, while also writing intricate arrangements that showcased the distinct styles of his band members. This balance allowed him to create original and cohesive sounds that were tailor-made for each piece, resulting in some of the most innovative jazz compositions in history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's innovative use of the voice as a musical instrument, as seen in his early piece, Creole Love Call. This song demonstrates his ability to incorporate the voice to add depth and color without lyrics. The piece features a call and response between the voice and reeds, with the voice starting smoothly and transitioning to a rougher sound by the end of the first chorus. The six-chorus structure showcases a variety of solos, from a muted trumpet solo in the second chorus to a soaring clarinet solo in the third. The climactic fifth chorus features a high-register call and response, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections. The sixth chorus returns to the initial structure, with the voice employing a "growl" technique. The tag features a vocal run and a dissonant trombone ending, highlighting Ellington's mastery in using voices and instruments interchangeably.

Ellington's use of voice as a layer of tone color is a consistent stylistic trait in his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, he showcased his ability to blend tight orchestration with unique tone colors. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing exemplifies this, combining Miley's vocal elements with Cox's instrumental voice. Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) further illustrates this approach, with Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton’s muted trombone introduction of the melody.

Ellington’s legacy is defined by his ability to empower his band members while creating cohesive and innovative compositions, making him one of the most influential figures in jazz history.

Well, I have this persistent feeling of lacking something. It's been with me since I was 14, entering my teenage life. And even now, at 17, it's still there. I thought I wanted a person more than anything else, but no one has caught my interest. Some boys have tried, but none of them have appealed to me. I often wonder what this peculiar situation is about. Over the past few years, I've tossed up several theories, but nothing concrete has stuck. So I continue to live my life, questioning my desires. A typical day at home is usually peaceful. My parents are both calm and get along well, even with me. We don't argue much, except when I try to assert my independence and vibrant personality. They're good people, and I think my lively nature makes me quite likeable. But today was different. As I wandered from room to room, looking for inspiration, I heard my mother scream from the kitchen. I rushed in and found her lying on the floor, obviously in pain. She told me to take her to the hospital. I carried her to the car and drove straight to the ER. The scent of disinfectant and sickness filled the air, but I was too focused on helping her. At the hospital, they took her to be examined. She had fallen while trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet.

So this study was all about proving that sticking to a Mediterranean diet (Med diet), especially if you've got a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", is tied to a lower risk of getting chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, and even dying from a stroke. The aMed diet is basically a tweak on the Med diet, with more plant-based foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, along with more monounsaturated fats and fish, and less animal products and saturated fats. It's okay to have a bit of alcohol too.

Previously, studies showed that following the Med diet is linked to a lower risk of dying from heart disease or cardiovascular problems, and in a trial, it was better than a low-fat diet for losing weight and lowering "bad" cholesterol in people who are overweight. But no one had looked into stroke or stroke deaths.

Now, this research followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 who didn't have heart disease or diabetes and were part of the Nurses' Health Study. Six times, from 1984 to 2004, they calculated an aMed diet score using food questionnaires. Over 95% of the nurses stayed in the study for the entire 20 years. These questionnaires were checked for accuracy. Reports of heart disease, fatal heart disease, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, death certificates, or even autopsies. If records weren't available, cases were considered "probable" and included in the study.

To get a better idea of each person's long-term diet, the study used average aMed scores from the repeated questionnaires. They also adjusted for things that might mess up the results, like age, smoking, body weight, menopause, hormone use, vitamin intake, alcohol, physical activity, and aspirin use.

They used something called Cox proportional-hazard modeling to see how an aMed score was linked to the risk of heart disease and stroke. In the end, they found that women who stuck to the Mediterranean diet the most (based on their aMed score) had a lower risk of getting heart disease and stroke. During the 20 years, they found 2391 cases of heart disease, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 deaths from heart disease or stroke. Women who were in the top group for aMed score had a 29% lower risk for heart disease and stroke compared to those in the bottom group (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

So, fast forward to 2007. The good ol' US of A found itself in a real pickle - a financial crisis that was as crushing as it was unexpected. Joblessness skyrocketed, the housing market went belly up, and some of America's biggest fish in the corporate pond were left floundering. The thing is, how did we end up here, and how do we keep it from happening again?

Well, let's rewind to the Clinton years, specifically 1999. The prez was eyeing a second term, and he figured the best way to boost his popularity was to relax lending restrictions. This move, combined with the pressure from shareholders, led to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac taking on a whole lot of sub-prime mortgages and repackaging them into CDOs and CDSs. When the borrowers couldn't make their loan payments, the banks found themselves in a right mess, and the consequences were felt throughout the economy.

There were plenty of factors that pushed the economy into a tailspin, one of which was the newfangled mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs were all the rage before the crisis, and they only made the economy more intertwined with the housing market. This left households and financial markets super vulnerable to even the smallest price changes.

As the housing bubble popped, the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities got a rude awakening. The top five U.S. investment banks reported a staggering $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which was about a third of the USA’s GDP. Things got so bad that Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch got sold off cheap, Lehman Brothers went kaput, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley had to become regular old commercial banks with heavy regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in the red, and they ended up under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That section of your narrative where you attempt to flex your writer's wings and soar to new heights, or where your readers may fall asleep and abandon ship. Dr. Merlin has often found herself screaming at her monitor when she encounters too much information, none of which is in a fun way.

Exposition isn't your friend. Your readers already know the basics, like "show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into lengthy passages where nothing happens, or where too much does. Exposition is the little demon sitting on your shoulder, whispering, "Get the history out of the way to get to the good parts" (though not to be confused with the other devil on your shoulder that wants to tell you every last detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition means sharing what happened with your audience, typically in straightforward prose. In film, it's when one character delivers a monologue of information, like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, the author is the one doing the telling.

Let's consider an example. As you read a story, you learn that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, got married in a grand style, and then witnessed her husband's murder. You wouldn't expect all of that to take up two pages, during which both characters only exchange a handful of lines. You'd expect the author to delve into the husband's character, showing by his words and actions how deeply he loved his wife. You'd also expect the heroine to reveal through her actions and thoughts how much his presence changed her life. A thorough introduction to the husband's character would let you connect emotionally with his fate and provide insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her dreams and beliefs as seen through his eyes, and so on. You'd mourn his death with her, growing more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you'd expect substance, not just the bare bones of the story: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you must provide that substance. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, continues*) Sometimes, it's tempting to rush through certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character, and you know he used to be in the Air Force, now works nights at a gas station, was married twice, has no kids, enjoys fishing on weekends, dreams of owning the gas station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

Provide the details.

Well, let me tell you about the news from Columbus, Ohio. It's a bit grim, but here it goes. First off, there was a live broadcast on NBC 4 this morning, and the headline was about a guy named Shad Hostettler who had stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. They showed his mug shot, and he looked like pure evil. They spent only a couple of minutes on it, which I think was appropriate given that the story was still developing. The only details they gave were that he had stabbed her multiple times and was arrested. I reckon they allocated a suitable amount of time to this news.

Next up was a story about an 18-year-old, Travis Buyers, who was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, but no arrests had been made. The SWAT Team was looking into it. This story seemed quite brief, and I think that was probably because the victim was a black man, or from a black neighborhood. Now, I've noticed for years that minorities often get overlooked when they're crime victims. If it's a white person, the media goes crazy, but if it's a minority, it's lucky if it gets mentioned.

Following that, the news covered a bullet hole discovered in a Med-Flight helicopter. They mentioned the area where it might have happened and that the bullet was a .22 caliber from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers are offering five grand for tips leading to the shooter's arrest.

There was also a robbery story about a UDF on Clime Road. The suspect was described as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. He was about six feet tall and weighed around 150 pounds. The news seemed to spend an unusual amount of time emphasizing his race.

And finally, they reported on Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He was sentenced for conspiring to distribute marijuana in large quantities from Texas to Ohio. Instead of saying he was sentenced to 25 years, they said "300 months". I'm not sure why that was, but they also mentioned he was Hispanic, which didn't seem particularly relevant to the story.

There is a special tie between brothers, a bond so strong it can't be broken. This link carries with it a mix of feelings, like love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Brothers understand each other in a way no one else can, and they often see themselves reflected in their sibling. It's in the direst of situations that this bond truly reveals itself, whether it's a force for good or ill. When these emotions surface, they come at a price. A part of understanding the feelings that stem from this fraternal bond is dealing with the fallout. When you look into your brother's eyes, you see not how others perceive you, but who you truly are. Your actions and their outcomes showcase your character. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers grapple with this theme and the emotions that come with it. Amidst a lush, vividly described setting, these two boys embark on a doomed journey. The story reaches its climax with Doodle facing death from his older brother's disappointment and pride. The theme is conveyed through the direct portrayal of the protagonist and his interactions with Doodle, as well as the narrator's perspective, which highlights the complex emotions the protagonist feels and his view of the world around him.

The protagonist's actions are driven by a single key emotion: pride. From their first outing together to their tragic last adventure, the protagonist harbors resentment towards Doodle. He yearns for a brother who can learn all his skills, like holding his breath underwater, running, or climbing, or even racing to Horsehead Landing. But Doodle is frail, born with a weak heart, making it unlikely he'd survive such activities. The young protagonist's dreams shatter when he realizes Doodle can't fulfill these expectations. He even entertains thoughts of suffocating Doodle with a pillow, showing his anger and frustration. Yet, Doodle's smile can melt his heart, giving him hope. This indicates that his conviction may not have been strong. Deep down, he cares for his brother.

The human brain is a complex and ingenious information-processing machine. As our technology has evolved from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain have also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. Keep in mind that these metaphors, while useful, have limitations and can lead to misunderstandings.

Information processing begins with sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrochemical signals. This information is repeatedly transformed by the brain's algorithms in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when you see a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines simple aspects like color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are to determine that you're seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the initial decisions made during bottom-up processing to speed up your recognition, like identifying it as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.

Once information is processed to a certain extent, an attention filter decides its importance and which cognitive processes should access it. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing each one individually. Conversely, you might pick out your name in a noisy room. There are numerous stages of processing, and the results are continually refined by attention.

The brain must store information before processing it. Memory types include sensory, working, and long-term. Information is first encoded, with specific types of encoding for each sensory stimulus. Verbal input, for instance, can be encoded structurally (what the word looks like), phonemically (what it sounds like), or semantically (what it means). Once stored, information must be maintained. Animal studies suggest that working memory, which holds information for around 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through specific neurons. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained by the structure of certain proteins.

There are various models for how knowledge is organized in the brain, based on human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model proposes that there are nodes representing concepts, linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley takes a swipe at the looming threats of advanced technology and the capitalist system that supports it, painting a grim picture in Brave New World. The society values collective unity over individuality, with citizens brainwashed from birth to chase instant happiness. The populace is essentially puppets in a grand scheme, under the thumb of the World Controller, who dictates their every move. Looking at Brave New World through the lens of Marxism, one can't help but notice Huxley's reservations about these developments. Terms like homogenization and reification reinforce the idea that Huxley's novel is a critique of the flaws in society's economic structures of his time.

Capitalism is openly mocked through the concept of false consciousness. Here, the common folk are blinded to the true nature of their economic standing, their interests solely driven by personal gain. This is the result of ideological control over the working class, which is clearly seen in the conditioning of Brave New World's citizens. The lower classes, like Delta and Gamma, lack their own will, with hypnopædia reinforcing a drive to consume and indulge, all manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, where a dominant group controls others, is evident here, with the lower classes unknowingly buying into the very system that oppresses them. Upper classes, while aware of this manipulation, do little to resist it, much like the few Alphas or Betas, such as Bernard, who simply accept their place. The interactions between social classes further illustrate the perceived oppression of capitalism.

There's no room for genuine relationships in Brave New World. Characters, even major ones, are one-dimensional, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism strips us of our free will and expression. Emotions are kept shallow, with men discussing women primarily based on their physical characteristics, and women openly talking about their encounters. The societal classes' contentment with their status indicates the socioeconomic impact of capitalism, reflecting Marxist views on the proletariat, who are falsely made to believe their superiority through their continued consumption and obedience.

I've been a student at University Park for a couple of years now, which means I've spent a good chunk of my college life navigating the sprawling campus. During my freshman year, I was stuck in the East Halls dorms, which were tucked away in the far east corner of campus. Walking to classes scattered across campus, like the Willard building near the center, could take up to 25 minutes, especially when the weather was bad. I got the scoop from an alumni that not long ago, the campus was much bigger, with vast empty plots of land that have since been filled with sports fields and new buildings like the Creamery and health services facility. As the campus continues to grow, getting from one place to another becomes increasingly challenging. The solution? Cycling, of course. But bikes alone won't solve the problem. Students need to adopt them, and the campus must be designed with cyclists in mind.

I had a chat with a friend who recently picked up cycling after a long break. He marveled at how great bikes are and wondered why he had ever stopped. "They’re the best way to get around," he said, "especially when you're short on time and need to save energy." Biking doesn't just benefit your body; it's also the most efficient mode of transport. A simple bowl of oatmeal and a little exercise can take you 30 miles or more. Currently, I live off campus, just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest move I made this year was buying a bike. Every day, I have classes in Thomas building, a 25-minute walk from my place, which cuts down to 5 minutes on a bike if I pedal fast. The only hiccup is that Pollock Road, the direct route to Thomas, isn't always easy to navigate, whether on bike or foot. Walking has its merits, but with my busy schedule, it's a luxury I can't afford. If I didn't have a bike, walking would be my only option, adding an extra 30-40 minutes to my daily commute. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add that to all the other time I'd spend walking to other classes, appointments, and so on—that’s more time than I can spare.
